eplace "macho" unions with more feminist models to campaigns linking labor and community issues and attempts to establish cross-border solidarity and a living wage.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aLabor unionsxOrganizingzUnited States. 0aSocial movementszUnited States. 4aLabor History. 4aSociology & Social Science.  aAFL-CIO union.  aAFL-CIO.  aAmerican labor movement.  aCollective bargaining.  aEmployee rights.  aIndustrial Relations.  aIndustrial relations.  aLabor activism.  aLabor disputes.  aLabor economics.  aSocialist Worker.  aThe U.S. labor movement history.  aThe U.S. labor movement.  aactors union.  across-border solidarity.  aeconomic justice.  afeminist union theory.  aglobal justice movement.  aincreased unions.  aindustrial economic relations.  ainspiring activist.  alabor and community issues.  alabor history.  alabor memberships.  alabor movement history.  alabor relations studies.  alabor responses.  alabor revival.  alabor social movements.  alabor studies.  alabor union history.  alabor union theory.  alabor-based movement-building.  aliving wage campaigns.  amobilized grassroots energy.  aneoliberal globalization.  anew labor movement.  aorganized labor.  apolitical activism.  arevived labor movement.  asocial struggles against racism.  asteelworkers union.  asteelworkers.  aunderstanding unions.  aunion activism.  aunion activist history.  aunion activists.  aunion members.  aunion memberships.  aunion organizers.  aunion theory.  aunionization.  aunions in america.  aunions.  aworkplace struggles.  awriters strike.  awriters union.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/97815017225